<page_title>Characterizing Amorphous Materials Using Pair Correlation Functions</page_title>
<text>Characterizing Amorphous Materials Using Pair Correlation Functions

The pair correlation functions (PCFs) obtained from X-ray or neutron diffraction experiments contain rich information about the structures of liquids, glasses (amorphous materials), and mixtures.

The following model shows an amorphous material A52.8B30.2C17 (where the small particles are A, the medium-size ones are B, and the larger ones are C). The model is such set that the A-B interactions are weak, whereas the A-C and B-C interactions are much stronger. Would the PCFs for the A-B, B-C and A-C pairs reveal the strengths of these interactions?

Run the simulation until the tape is full. Then STOP the simulation, and click on the &quot;Show pair correlation function&quot; buttons. They will bring up new windows, in which the PCFs will be shown.

 
   
(A=small-size particle, B=medium-size particle, C=large-size particle)

 

